vibrancy of Vietnamese spirituality are vividly portrayed in these twelve essays that shed light on the remarkable reflorescence of religion in this communist country. Ancestor worship, mediumship, sacrifices, and communal rituals have not only survived Vietnam’s reintegration into the capitalist world; they are intrinsic to the dramatic reshaping of its contemporary social and cultural life. Transnational Buddhism and Christianity challenge the political status quo as they answer conflicting aspirations for enlightenment, justice, national development and cultural identity. Making conceptual contributions to anthropology and comparative religion, this book provides insights from post-revolutionary Vietnam into the diverse passages to re-enchantment in the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aAvieli, Nir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, Horim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeVido, Elise Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEndres, Kirsten W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJellema, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhương, Phạm Quỳnh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamsay, Jacob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoucy, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThiện, Ðỗ, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/